 * @section c_vs_fortran C vs Fortran Equivalence
 * 
 * Each C example has a corresponding Fortran equivalent that produces identical output.
 * Key differences to understand:
 * 
 * **Array Ordering:**
 * - C: Row-major, data[NY][NX] with dimensions (y, x)
 * - Fortran: Column-major, data(NX, NY) with dimensions (x, y)
 * 
 * **Indexing:**
 * - C: 0-based (0 to N-1)
 * - Fortran: 1-based (1 to N)
 * 
 * **API Naming:**
 * - C: nc_* functions (e.g., nc_create, nc_def_dim)
 * - Fortran: nf90_* functions (e.g., nf90_create, nf90_def_dim)
 * 
 * **Dimension Order:**
 * - C: Slowest to fastest varying (time, level, lat, lon)
 * - Fortran: Fastest to slowest varying (lon, lat, level, time)
 * 
 * @section building_examples Building Examples
 * 
 * **CMake:**
 * @code
 * cmake -B build -DBUILD_EXAMPLES=ON
 * cmake --build build
 * ctest --test-dir build
 * @endcode
 * 
 * **Autotools:**
 * @code
 * ./configure --enable-examples
 * make
 * make check
 * @endcode
 * 
 * **Disable Examples:**
 * - CMake: `-DBUILD_EXAMPLES=OFF`
 * - Autotools: `--disable-examples`
 * 
 * @section fortran_requirements Fortran Requirements
 * 
 * Fortran examples require:
 * - Fortran 90+ compiler (gfortran, ifort, etc.)
 * - NetCDF-Fortran library (netcdf-fortran)
 * - CMake: `-DENABLE_FORTRAN=ON`
 * - Autotools: `--enable-fortran`
 * 
 * If Fortran support is disabled or netcdf-fortran is unavailable, Fortran examples
 * are automatically skipped.
 * 
 * @section output_validation Output Validation
 * 
 * All examples are validated against expected CDL (Common Data Language) output stored
 * in `examples/expected_output/`. This ensures examples continue producing correct output
 * across code changes.
 * 
 * To regenerate expected output:
 * @code
 * cd examples
 * ./generate_all_cdl.sh
 * @endcode
 * 
 * @section key_concepts Key NetCDF Concepts
 * 
 * **Dimensions:** Named axes that define array shapes (e.g., time, lat, lon)
 * 
 * **Variables:** Named data arrays with defined dimensions and types
 * 
 * **Attributes:** Metadata attached to variables or files (units, long_name, etc.)
 * 
 * **Coordinate Variables:** 1D variables sharing dimension names, providing axis values
 * 
 * **Unlimited Dimensions:** Dimensions that can grow (classic: one max, NetCDF-4: unlimited)
 * 
 * **Compression:** NetCDF-4 feature for reducing file size (deflate, shuffle filters)
 * 
 * **Chunking:** NetCDF-4 feature for optimizing I/O performance
 * 
 * **User-Defined Types:** NetCDF-4 feature for complex data structures (compound, enum, vlen, opaque)
 * 
